SUMMARY:Writing in the Galleries: Vital Ecosystems
DESCRIPTION:In this workshop\, we begin by looking closely at artworkŌĆöa
 sking what we see\, think\, feel\, and wonder. Together\, we'll explore t
 he artist's possible message and its social meaning\, then turn those ref
 lections into our own creative responses.  Whether you're a writer or sim
 ply curious to try something new\, you'll find inspiration here and a wel
 coming community to share the journey.  About the Exhibition&#160\;  Step
  into Mulyana: Vital EcosystemsŌöĆan imaginative\, immersive installation
  that transforms the museum into a vibrant\, crocheted\, underwater ecosy
 stem. Inspired by Indonesia's spectacular coral reefs\, artist Mulyana (b
 . 1984\, Indonesia) invites you to explore a handcrafted seascape where a
 rt and ecology meetŌĆösparking reflection on beauty\, fragility\, and our
  shared responsibility to protect the ocean.  What to Bringyour favorite 
 pencil (no pens).  a notebook or paper. Clipboards are available to borro
 w.  a phone or camera to take a picture of the art for later reference.  
 Know Before You GoArrive early\, check in\, and get ready for an on-time 
 start.Readwhere to find us\, where to park\, accessibility\, and museum g
 uidelines.About Your Facilitator  Dedaimia Whitney earned an MFA in ficti
 on from Indiana University under the direction of Scott Russell Sanders. 
 She taught creative writing at Franklin College for many years. She has s
 erved the museum as a docent since 2019. Her favorite works of art are th
 ose that are both visually stimulating and thought-provoking.
